data.content:
MSTest has `CollectionAssert` and more specific assertions that give **better failure messages** than `Assert.IsTrue`:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Instead of Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)
    Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0, "Expected at least one user");
    // Or:
    CollectionAssert.That.IsNotEmpty(users); // MSTest v3+

    // For exact count — gives "Expected:3 Actual:5" on failure
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // For "all match a condition" — no built-in CollectionAssert,
    // but always add a message to IsTrue:
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive),
        "Expected all users to be active");

    // Instead of Assert.IsTrue(x != null)
    var admin = users.Single(u => u.Role == "Admin");
    Assert.IsNotNull(admin);
}
```

**Key improvements:**

| Avoid | Prefer | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count == 3)` | `Assert.AreEqual(3, x.Count)` | Shows expected vs actual on failure |
| `Assert.IsTrue(x != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(x)` | Clearer failure message |
| `Assert.IsTrue(list.Count > 0)` | `Assert.AreNotEqual(0, list.Count)` | Descriptive failure |
| `Assert.IsTrue(cond)` | `Assert.IsTrue(cond, "msg")` | Always add a message when the condition isn't self-describing |

**Other useful `CollectionAssert` methods:**

```csharp
CollectionAssert.Contains(users, expectedUser);
CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);
CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreUnique(users);
CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expected, actual); // same items, any order
CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expected, actual);       // same items, same order
```

The general rule: prefer the **most specific assertion** available — it produces the most helpful failure output.
